    "in_trash": false,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "paragraph": {
      "rich_text": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": {
            "content": "There’s a little pattern on the tip of the airplane wing, the part that curves up towards the sky. Red and a deep purple blending into each other in a repetitive but evolving pattern. I was quite enthralled by it. Classic engineer brain: how did they make it. So I think that it’s a red background with horizontal purple zigzags one on top of each other. The thickness of the line that makes up the zigzag increases, with each one being thicker than the one below it. Then the thing that makes the pattern evolve is the fact that each zigzag line is slightly offset the the right when compared to the one below it, although my eyes are having trouble discerning if this is true. Scrap that! The truth has been discovered, the zigzags aren’t offset, rather they decrease in amplitude as they move towards the front of the plane (the difference in heigh between the peaks gets less). Well this has been an ",
            "link": null
          },
          "annotations": {
            "bold": false,
            "italic": false,
            "strikethrough": false,
            "underline": false,
            "code": false,
            "color": "default"
          },
